# Mini HFT Demo — GOOGL on Alpaca Paper Trading

## What this does
A 4-thread C++ HFT engine that trades GOOGL using Alpaca paper trading.
- Thread 1: Connects to Alpaca WebSocket, streams live GOOGL bid/ask
- Thread 2: Market-making strategy, quotes around mid price
- Thread 3: Risk guard, monitors position + P&L, has kill switch
- Thread 4: Order manager, simulates fills, tracks latency in nanoseconds

## Quick Start (Simulated mode — no API keys needed)
```bash
g++ -std=c++17 -O2 -pthread main.cpp -o hft_demo
./hft_demo
```
Runs immediately with a simulated GOOGL price feed.

## Live Mode (Real Alpaca data)

### Step 1 — Install dependencies
```bash
# Ubuntu / WSL
sudo apt update
sudo apt install libwebsocketpp-dev libboost-all-dev libssl-dev nlohmann-json3-dev

# macOS
brew install websocketpp boost openssl nlohmann-json
```

### Step 2 — Set your Alpaca paper trading keys
```bash
export ALPACA_KEY="YOUR_KEY_HERE"
export ALPACA_SECRET="YOUR_SECRET_HERE"
```
Get keys from: https://app.alpaca.markets → API (left sidebar)

### Step 3 — Build and run
```bash
g++ -std=c++17 -O2 -pthread main.cpp -lssl -lcrypto -lboost_system -o hft_demo
./hft_demo
```

## What you'll see
```
[GOOGL] Bid:175.02 Ask:175.08 Mid:175.05  Pos:+30  P&L:$1.42  Orders:1842/1290  Lat(us): avg=342 min=181 max=891
```

## What it demonstrates (for Google interview)
- Multithreading: 4 threads with clear separation of concerns
- Lock-free programming: std::atomic for market data + position
- Mutex-protected queues: order queue between strategy and order thread
- Latency measurement: nanosecond timestamps on every order
- Risk management: kill switch using std::atomic<bool>
- Market making strategy: inventory skew, spread quoting

## Project structure
```
main.cpp          — entire engine (single file for easy demo)
CMakeLists.txt    — cmake build config
README.md         — this file
```